Hub-effect: Hubs are populations that have direct connections to many populations in the WAN, e.g., Hong Kong, Beijing, New York. If the epidemic origin is a hub, the growth of local disease prevalence can be substantially reduced if a significant proportion of infections travel outward as the epidemic unfolds18. Let Di,c be the set of populations that are c degrees of separation from the epidemic origin in the WAN-SPT24. From the perspective of the importation process for a given population j ∈ Di,1 (i.e., directly connected to the epidemic origin), the prevalence in population i grows exponentially at rate λij = λi − ∑k ≠ jwik (see Fig. 2a and The WAN-SPT analysis in Methods for details). Figure 2d and Supplementary Fig. 3 show that with this hub-effect adjustment, fn(t|λij,αij) accurately characterizes the probability distribution of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
